impact:
• **Cuts earned compensation.** Roughly 70,000 future retirees per year—many in law‑enforcement, firefighting and air‑traffic control—would lose an average of $10,000‑$12,000 annually until age 62, shrinking real retirement income by up to 20 percent.:contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}

• **Retention paradox.** Agencies that rely on early‑retirement authority to refresh physically demanding jobs could see experienced employees hang on longer for a full Social Security benefit, undercutting workforce‑planning models.:contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}

• **Recruitment & equity concerns.** The supplement was designed to level FERS with private‑sector plans that integrate smoothly with Social Security; eliminating it widens the gap and may deter applicants for hard‑to‑fill positions while disproportionately harming middle‑income workers without large Thrift Savings Plan balances.:contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

• **‘Pay‑to‑keep‑your‑rights’ model.** Employees who decline at‑will status would see take‑home pay drop by ~$3,500 a year on a GS‑11 salary—effectively taxing workplace due‑process protections and pricing them out for lower‑paid staff.:contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

• **Merit‑system erosion.** Converting large segments of the workforce to at‑will fearful of summary removal revives the patronage risks Congress stamped out in the 1978 Civil Service Reform Act; whistle‑blower disclosures, union activity and scientific integrity could all be chilled.:contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

• **Savings highly uncertain.** CBO projects only modest deficit reduction (~$3 billion over ten years) because higher FERS contributions partly offset bonus severance payouts and turnover costs; any gains may be dwarfed by litigation and recruitment expenses.:contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}

• **Chills meritorious cases.** Roughly 30 % of MSPB appellants are lower‑graded employees earning under $60 k; a $400+ out‑of‑pocket cost—due up‑front—could deter legitimate challenges, especially whistle‑blower and discrimination claims that already carry retaliation risk. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}

• **Minimal fiscal upside.** CBO’s deficit‑reduction option to charge MSPB fees projected < $50 million over 10 years—< 0.001 % of federal outlays—because caseload declines offset revenue. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}  Any savings could be eroded by pro‑se litigants shifting to costlier district‑court venues.

• **Access‑to‑justice concerns.** Unlike Article III courts (which allow IFP waivers), the bill offers no fee waiver for hardship; critics argue it violates the merit‑system principle of ‘effective legal redress’ and will increase agency abuse of adverse‑action authority.

• **Savings potential, but evidence thin.** GAO estimates ineligible dependents may cost FEHB up to $1 billion a year, yet prior OPM pilot verifications captured only ~2 % of dependents; mandatory audits could recoup far less than projected while costing hundreds of millions to administer. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

• **Administrative drag on agencies.** HR offices would shoulder new paperwork burdens during open seasons and life‑event changes, diverting staff from mission work; smaller agencies with thin HR capacity could struggle to meet record‑retention rules. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

• **Privacy & equity risks.** Retaining sensitive documents for six years after coverage ends enlarges the attack surface for identity theft; same‑sex couples, adoptive parents, and guardians may face disproportionate hurdles proving eligibility.

• **Funding carve‑out precedent.** Permanently exempting OPM oversight dollars from congressional spending caps reduces future fiscal flexibility and creates a quasi‑entitlement for compliance contractors.
